<title type="html"><![CDATA[1980s Nostalgia • Hamleys catalogue from Xmas 1983]]></title>

<category term="1980s Nostalgia" scheme="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewforum.php?f=8" label="1980s Nostalgia"/>
<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=20&amp;p=47#p47"><![CDATA[
I love 80's nostalgia, and I love Christmas, so every now and then I trawl eBay for Christmas gift catalogues from way-back-when. One of my latest acquisitions is the Xmas 1983 Hamleys catalogue. Around about that time, my mum would drag me and my brother into London to do some shopping, and would drop us off in Hamleys toy store whilst she went and did other stuff. Hamleys would have an entire floor filled with tables, each one covered with electronic games all powered up and ready to play with. We're talking Munchman, BMX Style, Space Invaders, the lot during this golden age of gizmo games.<br /><br />It was just a fading memory, until now.<br /><br /><img src="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/fscratch/hamleys1.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/fscratch/hamleys2.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />The Hamleys catalogue has a section on electronic games and has photos of this department, and it really is as I remember it - utterly packed with games wherever you looked. There were barely any clear spaces on the counters! And most of the time it would be heaving with kids trying to play the latest Game&amp;Watch or whatever. Happy days.<br /><br />And here's what else you found there:<br /><br /><img src="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/fscratch/hamleys3.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />And of course:<br /><br /><img src="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/fscratch/hamleys4.jpg" alt="Image" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=54">NickH</a> — Sun Jun 26, 2011 5:12 pm — Replies 12 — Views 1367</p><hr />
]]></content>
